{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17602349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17602349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:24:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:24:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.63,0.21,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67269"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8382"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52721"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10146"},{"type":"tags","id":"10602"},{"type":"tags","id":"10604"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67269"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the menstrual cycle, basal body temperature shows a characteristic biphasic pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following days of the menstrual cycle is most likely associated with the initial rise in basal body temperature?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Day 2","Day 10","Day 14","Day 18","Day 27"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBasal body temperature demonstrates a biphasic pattern during the menstrual cycle. During the follicular phase (days 1-14), temperature remains relatively low. Following ovulation around \u003Cstrong\u003Eday 14\u003C/strong\u003E, progesterone secreted by the corpus luteum causes a thermogenic effect, raising basal body temperature by approximately 0.5\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis temperature elevation persists throughout the luteal phase until menstruation. Day \u003Cstrong\u003E2\u003C/strong\u003E is during menstruation when temperature is low. Day \u003Cstrong\u003E10\u003C/strong\u003E is mid-follicular phase with low temperature. Day \u003Cstrong\u003E14\u003C/strong\u003E marks ovulation and the initial temperature rise. Day \u003Cstrong\u003E18\u003C/strong\u003E and day \u003Cstrong\u003E27\u003C/strong\u003E are during the luteal phase when temperature is already elevated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Basal body temperature rises by 0.5\u00b0C after ovulation due to progesterone\u0027s thermogenic effect","Ovulation typically occurs around day 14 of a 28-day menstrual cycle","The temperature rise persists throughout the luteal phase until menstruation"],"references":["Hawkins SM, Matzuk MM. The menstrual cycle: basic biology. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2008;1135:10-8. doi: 10.1196/annals.1429.018. PMID: 18574203; PMCID: PMC2913133.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: E